I've enjoyed both 10,000,000 as well as this game. The match-3 mode is smooth and well done and the rpg elements keep the gameplay engaging and interesting.  However the graphics for this game is really blah, so much so sometimes I've trouble figuring out what those blobs of pixels are supposed to represent, and there are lots of them. The 8-bit graphics may have worked fine with the simpler 10,000,000, but it kind of stretched a little for this game where the 8-bitters are supposed to be clickable items. I'm not sure if the developer deliberately kept the graphics retro or he simply lacked the time and the resources to make it better. I'm not looking for 3D, state-of-the-art graphics. But something in the resolution and style of Jetpack Joyride would've made this game a more enjoyable experience.

Build a boat. You must.

FANTASTIC SEQUEL  If you've played 10000000 and enjoyed that, then you must buy this game. The game play is like 10000000 on steroids. Just like the original, it's almost like a puzzle RPG. There's much more "meat" to it. The pace of the game seems a bit more hectic, but in a good way. There's much more to do in terms of building up your character. The content is varied, so you aren't looking at the same background every time you go on a "run". Again, if you've played and enjoyed 10000000, then you must buy this game.  For those of you who haven't played 10000000... You must buy this game.

The game has been improved in every concievable way! Progression is multi-layered. This time you're not stuck in a single dungeon with same background for the rest of the game, you MUST BUILD A (big ass ship) BOAT, which as the game progresses gets bigger and more useful as you free various specialists, from dungeons you explore, who reward you by setting up various shops aboard your ever-expanding boat. The bejeweled part of "match-three-items" is more complex and fun than ever! Especially that now you can recruit the same monsters you fight in the dungeons as your special ultra-combo passé to help defeat the most powerful of foes! Playing this game in short bursts or in longer-binge sessions feels just as fun and rewarding. Highly recommended!
